div.p:
NOw having ſaid ſomewhat concerning the firſt part of the firſt point of the Cō
ſideration of thy ſelfe, which is, What thou art: it is neceſſary that we proceed. farther to the ſeconde part of this firſt point of Conſideration; which is, Who thou art. The Conſideration whereof doth containe in it the remembrance & reknowledgement of thy parentage, linage, and deſcent: the knowledge of thy ſtate of body, of thy vvealth, calling, dignity and wiſedome. To the goodneſſe and greatneſſe of which giftes the Philoſophers in former times haue attribured a great part of mās felicity;  calling Riches, Nobility, & Honors, the goods of fortune;
 Health, Strēgth & Beauty, they tearmed the goods of the body;
 Wiſedome, Learning and Vertue they eſteemed to be the goods of the Minde.
